\par }\pard \ql \fi-1800\li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 {\f1 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ql \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\page Defining Bot Personalities
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f1 Defining a bot personality consists of specifying values for a bot\rquote 
s various attributes and labeling the values with a name, such as \'93Fred\'94.  These attributes influence and control different aspects of a bot\rquote s behavior, such as how observant they are, or how well they can aim their weapons.
\par 
\par While fairly straightforward, a bot personality database does contain a lot of data.  It is strongly recommended that interested players refer to the BotCampaignProfile.db and BotProfile.db files which contain the bot personalities for the retail game.

\par 
\par Data within a bot database is always contained within a }{\i\f1 data block}{\f1  which has the following form:
\par 
\par \tab <data block type> [<data block name>]
\par \tab \tab <attribute> = <value>
\par \tab \tab <attribute> = <value>
\par \tab \tab \'85
\par \tab \tab <attribute> = <value>
\par \tab End
\par 
\par <data block type> can be:
\par 
\par Default
\par }\pard \ql \li360\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f1\fs20 This data block defines default values for all attributes.  
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par Skin <skin name>
\par }\pard \ql \li360\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f1\fs20 This data block defines a \'93skin\'94 (player model) for later use.  It can contain a single attribute of \'93Model\'94
 which should be set to the name of the .mdl file without its extension.  The example below defines a skin for czero\\models\\player\\arctic.mdl:
\par }{\f1 
\par \tab Skin TerroristSniperSkin
\par \tab \tab Model = arctic
\par \tab End
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par Template <template name>
\par }\pard \ql \li360\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f1\fs20 Templates define values for a related set of attributes.  Templates are then used by specific bot data blocks to \'93inherit\'94
 data values.  See the Data Inheritance section for more information.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par <template name>[+<template name> \'85] <bot name>
\par }\pard \ql \li360\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f1\fs20 Defining a data block via the use of one or more template names creates a bot definition.  The values the bot\rquote s attributes receive are \'93inherited\'94
 by starting with the values in the Default data block, and then overwriting any attribute values found in the template blocks listed, evaluated from left to right. 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ql \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Attribute Reference
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f1 
\par }{\b\f1 Name
\par Value}{\f1 : A string. If the name contains spaces, surround it with quotes (ie: \'93Cliffe\'94)
\par Description: The bot\rquote s name.  
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 Skill
\par Range}{\f1 : 0 to 100
\par }{\b\f1 Description}{\f1 : Defines the overall \'93skill\'94 of the bot. Low skill bots have terrible aim and don\rquote t look around very much, whereas high skill bots can 
have extremely good aim, try to check as many corners and hiding spots as they can, and know subtle things like using the knife to run faster, switching to the pistol when out of ammo, and so on.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 Aggression
\par Range}{\f1 : 0 to 100
\par }{\b\f1 Description}{\f1 : Determines how aggressively a bot behaves. High aggression bots pay less attention to \'93danger\'94
 (ie: where teammates have died previously), are more likely to rush, and less likely to retreat.  Low aggression bots are just the opposite.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 ReactionTime 
\par Range}{\f1 : 0.2 to 0.5 seconds
\par }{\b\f1 Description}{\f1 : Determines the reaction time of a bot. A bot\rquote s \'93reaction time\'94 is the delay between when a visual or audio event occurs and the bot becomes \'93aware\'94
 of it, and can begin to act upon it. This simulates the time it takes a human to process incoming stimuli and become \'93conscious\'94 of it.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 AttackDelay
\par Range}{\f1 : Seconds of time before bot will open fire after acquiring a victim
\par }{\b\f1 Description}{\f1 : After a bot has become aware of an enemy, this duration must also elapse before it will begin firing upon its vic
tim. This attribute is primarily used for easy bots, allowing novice players additional time to react and aim their weapon before the bot opens fire.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 Teamwork
\par Range}{\f1 : 0 to 100
\par }{\b\f1 Description}{\f1 : Defines how cooperative and \'93team oriented\'94 the bot is.  High teamwork bots are more likely to obey radio commands and stay with their teammates.  Low teamwork bots tend to \'93go rogue\'94 and do their own thing.
\par 
\par \page }{\b\f1 WeaponPreference
\par Value}{\f1 : \'93none\'94 or a buy alias such as \'93m4a1\'94
\par }{\b\f1 Description}{\f1 : Defines the bot\rquote s weapon preference.  A
 bot can have many WeaponPreference definitions in a row, specifying a prioritized list (earlier ones are favorite over later ones) of weapons the bot will try to buy or pick up from the ground.  A preference of \'93none\'94
 will cause the bot to buy a random weapon.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 Difficulty
\par Value}{\f1 : EASY | NORMAL | HARD | EXPERT
\par }{\b\f1 Description}{\f1 : Defines the difficulty categories where this bot is used. Note that these flags can be combined, such as \'93NORMAL + HARD\'94, meaning the bot can be used on either the Normal or Hard difficulty setting.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 VoicePitch
\par Value}{\f1 : 85 to 120 (100 is unshifted)
\par }{\b\f1 Description}{\f1 : Defines the pitch shift value this bot will use for its \'93chatter\'94.  Lower values create lower pitched voices.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 Skin
\par Value}{\f1 : 0-4 or <skin name>
\par Description: Defines which \'93skin\'94
 to select when the bot joins the game.  Values 1 through 4 map to the associated skins on the player menu in game. A value of 0 selects a skin at random.  If a <skin name> is given, the skin must have been previously defin
ed using a Skin data block.  Skin data blocks can refer to custom skins other than the default CZ skins.  Custom skins should be placed in czero\\models\\player\\<skin name>\\<skin name>.mdl.
\par }\pard \ql \fi-1800\li1800\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1800\itap0 {\f1 
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par }{\f1\fs20 
\par }{
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ql \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\i\f1\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\page Data Inheritance in the Bot Database File
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f1 Defining a bot perso
nality involves specifying a dozen or more parameters.  If you want to create several bots, this means defining quite a lot of data.  To help organize and modularize this bot personality data, the Bot Database makes use of a very simple data \'93
inheritance\'94 mechanism.
\par 
\par Here is an example of how the inheritance mechanism works:
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f28\fs20 Default
\par     Color = Grey
\par     Shape = Circle
\par     Size = Medium
\par     Weight = Average
\par     Material = Wood
\par End
\par 
\par Template RedSquare
\par     Color = Red
\par     Shape = Square
\par End
\par 
\par RedSquare MyRedSquare
\par     Size = Small
\par End
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par The \'93Default\'94 entry defines initial values of all attributes, in this case \'93Color\'94, \'93Shape\'94, \'93Size\'94, \'93Weight\'94, and \'93Material\'94.  The next entry is a \'93Template\'94, which defines a data type named \'93RedSquare\'94
 that sets the attributes \'93Color\'94 and \'93Shape\'94 to \'93Red\'94 and \'93Square\'94, respectively.  Finally, the last entry actually instantiates an object of type \'93RedSquare\'94 called \'93MyRedSquare\'94 which sets \'93Size\'94 to \'93Small
\'94. The resulting values for \'93MyRedSquare\'94 are:
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f28\fs20   Color = Red
\par   Shape = Square
\par   Size = Small
\par   Weight = Average
\par   Material = Wood
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par \'93Weight\'94 and \'93Material\'94 remain at their default of \'93Average\'94 and \'93Wood\'94, since neither \'93RedSquare\'94 or \'93MyRedSquare\'94 changed them.
\par 
\par \page The bot database allows for a crude form of \'93multiple inheritance\'94 as well:
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f28\fs20 Default
\par     Color = Grey
\par     Shape = Circle
\par     Size = Medium
\par     Weight = Average
\par     Material = Wood
\par End
\par 
\par Template RedSquare
\par     Color = Red
\par     Shape = Square
\par End
\par 
\par Template BigAndHeavy
\par     Size = Large
\par     Weight = Heavy
\par End
\par 
\par RedSquare+BigAndHeavy MyBigRedSquare
\par     Material = Iron
\par End
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par In this example, a new entry has been added called \'93BigAndHeavy\'94 which sets the attributes \'93Size\'94 and \'93Weight\'94 to \'93Large\'94 and \'93Heavy\'94. Notice that the instance of \'93MyBigRedSquare\'94 now lists both \'93RedSquare\'94 and 
\'93BigAndHeavy\'94 as its type, combined with the addition symbol \'93+\'94.  The final values of \'93MyBigRedSquare\'94 are:
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f28\fs20 Color = Red
\par Shape = Square
\par Size = Large
\par Weight = Heavy
\par Material = Iron
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par \'93Color\'94 and \'93Shape\'94 were inherited from \'93RedSquare\'94, \'93Size\'94 and \'93Weight\'94 from \'93BigAndHeavy\'94, and \'93Material\'94 was set directly by the definition of \'93MyBigRedSquare\'94. Any number of basic types can be \'93added
\'94 together in this way.
\par 
\par With multiple inheritance, data is copied to the object in a left to right order.  If both \'93RedSquare\'94 and \'93BigAndHeavy\'94 had values for the same attribute, the final value would match the one in \'93BigAndHeavy\'94 since it came after \'93
RedSquare\'94.
\par 
\par \page How is this actually used with bot data?  It is very useful to break bot attributes into \'93weapon preferences\'94 and \'93difficulty levels\'94. For example, here are some example templates for difficulty levels:
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f28\fs20 Template Expert
\par     Skill = 90
\par     Aggression = 90
\par     ReactionTime = 0.2
\par     Difficulty = EXPERT
\par End
\par 
\par Template Hard
\par     Skill = 75
\par     Aggression = 75
\par     ReactionTime = 0.25
\par     Difficulty = HARD
\par End
\par 
\par Template Normal
\par     Skill = 50
\par     Aggression = 50
\par     ReactionTime = 0.4
\par     AttackDelay = 0.7
\par     Difficulty = NORMAL
\par End
\par 
\par Template Easy
\par     Skill = 0
\par     Aggression = 20
\par     ReactionTime = 0.5
\par     AttackDelay = 1.5
\par     Difficulty = EASY
\par End
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par \'85 and here are some templates defining weapon preferences:
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f28\fs20 Template Rifle
\par     WeaponPreference = m4a1
\par     WeaponPreference = ak47
\par     WeaponPreference = famas
\par     WeaponPreference = galil
\par     WeaponPreference = mp5
\par End
\par 
\par Template Sniper
\par     WeaponPreference = awp
\par     WeaponPreference = sg550
\par     WeaponPreference = g3sg1
\par     WeaponPreference = scout
\par     WeaponPreference = famas
\par     WeaponPreference = galil
\par     WeaponPreference = mp5
\par End
\par 
\par \page Template Shotgun
\par     WeaponPreference = xm1014
\par     WeaponPreference = m3
\par     WeaponPreference = famas
\par     WeaponPreference = galil
\par     WeaponPreference = mp5
\par End
\par 
\par Template Shield
\par     WeaponPreference = shield
\par     WeaponPreference = m4a1           // in case shield is disallowed
\par     WeaponPreference = ak47
\par     WeaponPreference = famas
\par     WeaponPreference = galil
\par     WeaponPreference = mp5
\par End
\par 
\par Template Spray
\par     WeaponPreference = p90
\par     WeaponPreference = tmp
\par     WeaponPreference = mac10
\par     WeaponPreference = mp5
\par End
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par These templates allow the easy creation of a bot named \'93John\'94 who likes to use rifles and is a pretty hard opponent:
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f28\fs20 Hard+Rifle John
\par     Skin = 3
\par     VoicePitch = 97
\par End
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par Creating a bot named \'93Fred\'94 who also likes rifles, but is a complete newbie, is just as simple:
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f28\fs20 Easy+Rifle Fred
\par     Skin = 2
\par     VoicePitch = 110
\par End
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1 
\par By mixing and matching templates, a large number of bots can be created quickly. This arrangement also facilitates \'93tuning\'94 bot behaviors - if \'93hard\'94 bots are too hard, the values can be changed in just one place (the \'93Hard\'94
 template), and all hard bots will be updated as a result.
\par 
\par Modularizing bot personality data in this way keeps a large amount of data organized and manageable. 
\par 
\par 
\par 
